cs.SI, cs.SD, cs.SOC, cs.CYBER, cs.IR 

The paper uses graph-theoretic methods to analyze the Twitter debate surrounding NHS England's controversial care.data scheme. It focuses on understanding how influence and interest propagate within the network of users and how information flows through the Twitter network. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.SD (Software Engineering). The paper also discusses the behavior of dynamic processes on the network, which suggests the sub-category cs.SOC (Social and Behavioral Sciences). Additionally, the paper deals with the classification of users by their roles in directing the flow of information through the network, which could fall under the sub-categories cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval).
